{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473649"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:12:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2668"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2668"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.19,0.66,0.06,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108441"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2668"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90831"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38952"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108441"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother with a 36-hour history of intermittent distress. His distress began suddenly the previous afternoon and lasted a few minutes before he appeared to settle. He has since had several more episodes, which appear to entirely resolve between each episode. During these episodes, his mother has noticed he has become especially pale, which also resolves spontaneously. She thinks his abdomen may be swollen and has noticed that his stools have been loose today. He has vomited several times since these episodes began , and his mother says the vomitus has changed in colour from milky to yellow/green. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 180/min. His abdomen is distended but soft.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT chest, abdomen and pelvis","Abdominal X-ray","Abdominal ultrasound","No investigation is required","Contrast enema"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has clinical features concerning for intussusception. This often presents with episodic distress, bilious vomiting, and abdominal distention. The \u0027red currant jelly\u0027 stool is a relatively late symptom of intussusception, and the diagnosis should still be suspected in the absence of this classic symptom, often stools can be loose or normal early on. The triad of intussusception consisting of recurrent abdominal pain, \u0027red-currant jelly\u0027 stool and a palpable abdominal mass, is seen in only one-third of patients. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Victorian Royal Children\u0027s Hospital guidelines presently recommend \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E to confirm the diagnosis of intussusception. The ultrasound will demonstrate the classical \u0027target sign\u0027 (concentric alternating echogenic and hypoechoic bands). In childhood intussusception, abdominal ultrasound performed by a trained paediatric ultrasonographer has high sensitivity (\u0026gt;98%) and specificity (\u0026gt;98%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast enemas\u003C/strong\u003E can be used both diagnostically and therapeutically in the setting of intussusception. However, the small risk of perforation makes this less likely to be the most appropriate first-line investigation in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo investigation\u003C/strong\u003E would not be a wise choice, as the presentation of intussusception overlaps with many other serious conditions (e.g. bowel obstruction, Meckel diverticulum) which must be ruled out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA normal \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E does not exclude intussusception. An abdominal X-ray may be justified if there are signs of bowel obstruction or perforation from the intussusception; however, they are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest, abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in the diagnosis of intussusception, particularly due to the high dose of radiation it incurs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal ultrasound is the appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis of intussusception."],"references":["Intussusception guideline. In: The Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne \u2013 Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Intussusception_Guideline/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90831"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2668"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90831"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-11T15:19:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T15:19:31+09:30"},